Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Status hearing on December 6, 2022 at 08:30 am.
Defendant enters a plea of NOT GUILTY to all counts. Bond already set and is to continue.

3:03 PM Court calls case. DA Kelz states appearances. Defendant Shane B. Kielski in court.  Attorney Daniel Francis Snyder in court for Shane B. Kielski.  Attorney Karl J. Kelz in court for State of Wisconsin. DA Kelz calls witness: David Wesenick a Deputy with the Price County Sheriff's Office. Witness sworn. Direct questioning of the witness by DA Kelz. Attorney Snyder stipulates to identification of the defendant. Cross examination by Attorney Snyder. Re-direct by DA Kelz. Re-cross by Attorney Snyder. Witness excused. Off record at 3:17 pm for prosecution to retrieve an exhibit. Back on the record at 3:19 PM all appearances are as previously stated. DA Kelz recalls witness to the stand. Judge questions parties as to witness testifying at counsel table. Parties agree.  DA Kelz questions witness in regards to Exhibit #1 which has been marked and identified. Attorney Snyder objects to the court receiving the exhibit. Court overrules Attorney Snyder's objection. Exhibit received by the court. Argument by Attorney Snyder. Argument by DA Kelz. Court finds probable cause exists that a crime was committed and binds DE over for trial. Information filed, acknowledged by parties and reading waived. Proceed to arraignment.
Preliminary hearing on October 17, 2022 at 03:00 pm.
Order for Appointment of an Attorney, Affidavit of indigency
Petition for Appointment of an Attorney, Affidavit of indigency

10:02 AM Defendant Shane B. Kielski in court.  Attorney Karl J. Kelz in court for State of Wisconsin. Defendant states he has not received the criminal complaint. Court states charges and maximum penalties. DA Kelz provides the defendant with a copy of the criminal complaint. Defendant questions the court on portions of the criminal complaint. Complaint acknowledged, reading waived. Notice of right to attorney given to Defendant. Bond already set and is to continue. Preliminary hearing requested, time limits waived. Court explains the procedures of the initial appearance. Court orders Pre-trial conference be scheduled for 8/9/2022 at 3:30 PM.
